    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/06-rl-infra/01-anatomy-rl-system.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Online RL is a TWO-ENGINE LOOP, not a one-engine job: the training data does not exist on disk, it is generated by the model being trained, then scored, then consumed to update that same model \u2014 so an inference engine and a training engine run inside one loop on weights that change every step.; There are six invariant components (actor/policy, rollout engine, reward/verifier, learner, reference, experience buffer) plus a seventh controller; frameworks differ only in WHERE these run and WHO coordinates them.; The canonical dataflow is a serial relay: sample -> rollout -> reward -> advantage -> buffer -> learn(E epochs) -> weight-sync; two arrows have NO SFT analogue \u2014 the data is manufactured in-loop, and the fresh weights must be synced back into the generator.; Tension 1: generation (memory-bandwidth-bound decode) and training (compute-bound) want OPPOSITE hardware, so their best software (vLLM/SGLang vs FSDP/Megatron) uses INCOMPATIBLE weight layouts \u2014 you must run both stacks and bridge them, and that bridge IS the weight-sync problem.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  rlanat-two-profiles-bridge\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
