    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/07-inference-serving/05-trtllm-tgi-stacks.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Decode is memory-bandwidth-bound: each generated token re-reads the full weight matrix, so tokens/sec is ultimately capped by HBM-bandwidth \u00f7 model-bytes-read. Every serving stack is fighting to approach this ceiling.; The through-line tension: the more a runtime commits to one hardware target, the more aggressive its optimizations (kernel selection, fusion, machine-code emission) \u2014 but the less portable it becomes. Peak-performance and portability sit at opposite ends of one axis.; WHY TensorRT-LLM is fast = AOT compilation. PyTorch runs a Python interpreter that dispatches many separate CUDA kernels per layer, bouncing intermediate tensors through HBM. TensorRT traces the whole forward pass, fuses ops into a few mega-kernels, and emits a hardware-specific binary engine \u2014 fewer launches, less HBM traffic, no runtime dispatch.; The serving topology differs by stack: Triton wraps a TRT-LLM engine as pre/post/engine sub-models with the Executor doing in-flight batching; TGI splits a low-latency Rust router from a Python model server over an IPC socket. Same job, different process boundaries.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  trtllm-kv-budget-and-scheduler\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
